cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.MA, cs.SY, cs.MM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with the estimation of local scattering function (LSF) from a large set of measurements collected in the DRIVEWAY'09 measurement campaign, which focuses on scenarios for intelligent transportation systems (ITSs). Information theory plays a crucial role in the estimation of channel parameters from the measured data. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper focuses on vehicular communication channels, which are relevant for networking and internet architecture in intelligent transportation systems. 
3. cs.MA (Multiagent Systems): The paper deals with scenarios for intelligent transportation systems (ITSs), which involve multiple agents (vehicles) communicating with each other. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper deals with the estimation of channel parameters for nonstationary vehicular channels, which is relevant for control systems in intelligent transportation systems. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper deals with the estimation of time-frequency-varying power delay profile (PDP) and the time-frequency-varying Doppler power spectral density (DSD) from the local scattering function (LSF), which is relevant for multimedia applications in intelligent transportation systems.
